attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit LSB executable, ARM, EABI4 version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, stripped

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered unknown. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This ELF binary is a Linux botnet agent, likely a variant of Gafgyt (BASHLITE) or Mirai, tailored for ARM-based IoT devices. It demonstrates classic malicious behaviors including: 1) Rival Malware Termination: Function sub_ab90 scans /proc/net/tcp to identify processes occupying specific ports and iterates through /proc/[pid]/exe and /proc/[pid]/fd to kill competing botnet instances. 2) Process Obfuscation: It uses prctl (via sub_1162c) to spoof its process name and setsid (sub_117d8) to daemonize and detach from the terminal. 3) Cryptographic Routines: Function sub_8254 implements a stream cipher (ChaCha20/Salsa20) indicated by the 'expand 32-byte k' constant, commonly used for C2 communication or string decryption. 4) Network Command & Control: The binary establishes persistent connections using socket, connect, and poll, targeting local and remote infrastructure. Relevant IOCs include its reliance on /proc reconnaissance paths and the Salsa20-based encryption function.
